items.content_html:
Summary

The new script does the following:

  • Read a specific chromestatus page to get information about current, nightly, and beta versions of Chrome for Desktop and Chrome for Android
  • "Guess" (and check) the URL for the release notes of the last current Chrome for desktop / Chrome for android
  • update the local BCD files chrome.json, chrome_android.json, and webview_android.json`.

Once landed, the goal is to run it once and manually create a PR for the change. After this, the plan is to add an action to do that automatically and create a PR with the change to the browser files.

Notes:

  • script should be run in the directory containing "chrome.json" / "chrome_android.json".
  • I found a chromestatus bug that returns an invalid JSON file. This script works around the problem. This is well commented on in the bug. We will follow up with Google, but not blocking
  • There is no definitive way to find the URL of the release notes, so I guess it (in a function where I test if it works, checking if the page HTTP status is 200).
  • Assumed that:
    • "stable" in chromestatus is "release" in BCD
    • "beta" is "beta"
    • ""canary" (not "dev") is "nightly"
      These are constants in the code, so it is trivial to change this mapping
  • Errors and warnings are logged on the console; this will be done while working on using it as a GitHub action.
  • Chromestatus doesn't have the whole history of release: if there is a gap, the script will log a warning.

Test results and supporting details

Manually tested.

Related issues

Part of the automation project.
items.title: Add script to update {chrome|chrome_android|webview_android}.json with new browser versions

items.content_html:
Summary

Resolves #20795

Some but not all notes entries mention bug tickets that especially resolve a missing functionality for feature completeness against the standard, that for I've included this one within the new impl_url entry, but not the previous, "original" bug ticket (with which the ticket has been partially implemented) for two reasons:

  • easier implementation: I would have needed to research the original ticket with the partial implementation
  • relevance: From my understanding the impl_url entries relevance is mainly about "feature completeness", so it would be more relevant to have an insight into the remaining work, than an already resolved ticket.
